} else if (content.type === 'resource') {
          const resource = content.resource;
          if ('text' in resource) {
            output += `[Resource: ${resource.uri}]\n${resource.text}\n`;
          } else {
            // blob variant
            output += `[Resource: ${resource.uri} (${resource.mimeType || 'application/octet-stream'})]\n`;
            output += `[Binary data: ${resource.blob.length} bytes]\n`;
          }
```

It seems that if it’s a text resource and the mime type isn’t text/plain (the use case I’m interested in is text/xml), the mime type will get lost at this point. The LLM will probably figure it out anyway, but if (‘text’ in resource && resource.mimeType != ‘text/plain’) we ought to put the mime type in parentheses after the uri, like we do in the binary blob case.

The use case I’m thinking of is when MCP gives you the program documentation, but it’s lightly marked up with XML for italics etc., and the LLM can just ignore the italics and read what the text says.

Some LLM’s (I’m looking at DeepSeek R1 here) will complain vociferously in the chain of thought that they were given XML they’re weren’t warned about, … and then go and do the right thing anyway.

